,Recommended,254200,26718575,"Posted: 20 November, 2016",all,form,"Well, since the single developer kicked me from the discord channel today and announced that he hates me and called me an antagonistic ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, I figured this is a good time to write a review of the game.1. Game design seems like the dev did try to cover many bases and be thorough.  I left the game several months ago and came back a few days ago, and a lot of tech has changed dramatically and there are many more buildable structures.  It has become much more complicated in a matter of a few months.  I.E., you might have to relearn a lot of things if you leave and return later.  The overall concept of the game seems to be focused on automation, which is expensive short-term and time saving long-term, as in many automation games.1.25. As someone else has said recently, this game's progress is very linear compared to games in a similar genre.  They also said it better than me when they described the dev's forcing of a set pathway based on his vision of how the game should be played, and how relatively inflexible progress is in this game. Some changes/nerfs that have been implemented have forced that, for example making underground smelting extremely impractical or non-functional.  It forces everyone to do things one way: The dev’s way.  I have often thought that the dev doesn’t want anyone to do anything he didn’t originally plan on them doing in his game.1.5. Automation elements similar to factorio include building ingots from smelters, heavy use of conveyers, and eventual (much later than in factorio, except research-fueling parts) automation of building components to build higher tier products.  This game uses storage hoppers as the primary transfer device instead of inserters in factorio.1.75. There is a tech tree and research, probably continually getting updates along with the tech.  I've never had any major issues with it, but the components for research were very simple several months ago and are probably still the same.  It's the volume of resources needed and the power consumption of a research lab that limit research speeds.2. Music is not very good IMO, about on par with Empyrion for that.  It's adequate.3. Game seems generally stable, not many crashes.4. There are still some multiplayer glitches (such as doubling items) mostly related to delays, lag and bandwidth oddities that result in items not being picked up promptly, objects not loading visually correctly/delaying being shown, etc., plus IMO the game demands pretty high bandwidth from users when doing multiplayer servers with large bases.  Maybe he's corrected this, but I doubt it.5. The game has what I would consider a pretty rudimentary tower defense system.  There are flying enemies (insectoids) that surge at intervals and attack your central hub, originating from 4 directions at approximately 90-degree angles away from your hub where there are hives or overminds (or whatever he calls them).  There are no pathing considerations, excepting that I think they do not go through original/unaltered naturally-formed mountains.  Otherwise, they travel in a straight line from source to target (hub).  There is a spiderbot utility NPC which can be used to aid in tower defense and now has several upgrades to damage and power reserves, etc., and I believe your personal helperbot also has a basic gun upgrade.  You have several tiers of turrets and a range of consumable missiles to defend your hub with.  Defense of the hub involves destroying the enemies before they can inflict enough damage to bring your hub down to 0% life.  The enemies drop items, mostly inert items that can be recycled later in the game, and a few items that are useful (perhaps now even critical to building certain things) and drop rarely.  The dev long ago told me that he didn't believe in the philosophy of losing progress through enemies destroying your base/etc., so that philosophy affects how the tower defense is played.  Today, just before banning me, the dev told me that pathing calculations for a 3-dimensional game like this would result in unreasonable amounts of calculations, probably especially for an online multiplayer game, so that's why enemy pathing isn't implemented to go around your buildings/etc.  The enemy spawns increase in frequency, number and tier/HP based on something called ""threat,"" which I believe is affected by how much power you generate (and possibly other factors I don't recall).6. The game IS steam-compatible for public servers, but right now there is only one public server (and another one for patreons) and AFAIK it has stayed that way ever since public servers were made available.  The dev says at present there are about 140 private servers, but the central communication hub for the game (discord channel) doesn't have more than 1-3 of the servers' users/admins on it usually, and one of them is the public server owner.  Private servers and password-protected servers are not listed in the server list in-game, so it makes it feel very quiet.7.  Last time I made a large base capable of charging OET (several months ago), I had significant framerate drops in the above ground world running the game fullscreen on a 1080p display on my i7-4930k @4ghz, 16gb 1600mhz ram, GTX770 graphics card, Samsung EVO 840 ssd in Win7Pro, medium settings.8. The dev has a massive chip on his shoulder.  He is sarcastic, rude, and verbally abusive if given the chance.  He has the potential to be very helpful, but your words have to conform to a specific format for him to be receptive enough to give helpful information without also being extremely rude.  He and I do not get along, mostly because I have differing opinions and express them freely.  The dev does NOT like (and in my opinion doesn't comprehend) impulsive initial impressions of things, although his own highly reactive manner (like putting a 9-volt battery to your tongue) suggests that he bases his opinions of people and their statements on knee-jerk reflex responses, very much like most people with a persecution complex.  He would disagree that he is very intolerant of other opinions and feedback that differs from what he believes about his game, and he would disagree that he is unfair to many people, but in fact he is very clique-ish and only tolerates certain types of feedback, his methods, etc., from an established group of people.The easiest way to get on his bad side is to say ""this item/equipment/etc. isn't very useful,"" at which point he will almost always highlight how invalid and wrong you are, then sometimes demand to know why you feel that way so he can tell you that’s wrong too.  Today, he accused me of disagreeing with him about pathing being too computationally demanding for the enemies (which I did not disagree with, I only stated that there was no pathing and it results in a more simplified/limited tower defense system).  It didn’t matter that his accusation was provably false.  I asked him not to talk to me because all we do is argue, and he used it as an excuse to ban me from his discord. He stated that a number of people had blocked me in the communication, which while possibly true does not change the fact that he was the only person I “sparred with” in the entire time I was talking, and then only because he always reacted to everything I said because I have opinions that don’t often conform to general views and I defend my views as vehemently as he forces his.  It takes 20 minutes to prove yourself correct, but only 2 seconds to be wrong in his eyes.  You are guilty until proven innocent.If you are very fresh, he will tolerate you briefly.  However, if he doesn’t agree with you almost immediately, he absolutely wants to believe you are wrong and will push that personal agenda.He is, at once, the single most important aspect of this game and its biggest detriment because of his extremely thin tolerance of other views.  I recommend the game, but the dev is not a nice person."
