76561198035537734,Recommended,254200,31004640,Posted: 7 April,all,Bäume,"Basically Minecraft with techmods without all the weirdness that comes from Minecraft with techmods (pickaxe into nuclear reactor, what?).It is very addicting to automate everything, but this is not all. This game has also tower defense elements, as you have to protect your base and certain buildings from regular waves of enemies with turrets and proper logistics, to keep them working.Sadly the game also has some drawbacks. Especially the depth of the map is annoying. Just getting from T1 to T2 ores needs you to dig hundreds of blocks down which also means you then have to create ways to transport energy down, ressources up and a way for yourself to get fast up and down. And this game has actually four tiers. There are ways to make this easier, but those arrive quite late (e. g. a quarry that digs a 3x3 shaft down so you can immediately use a elevator).Also the tech tree is quite weird at times. For example, it takes hours till you are able to use mincarts and when you have them, you simply don't need them anymore.The game has also some technical issues. The UI is ugly as hell (and feels like it is done for a tiny resolution) and the draw distance is quite low. Also items on conveors are invisible regulary.Other than that it is a fine game if you like fiddling around with machines and automation. It is better than Minecraft with mods in that area."
76561198092496411,Recommended,254200,17972792,"Posted: 10 September, 2015",all,Aparantis,"(This is a long description, skip to the pros and cons below if you don't want to spend much time on my review)My initial impression of the game wasn't great, which was largely thanks to the greatest difference between stable and beta branches in a game I've ever seen.   Once I opted into the beta, and selected some easier difficulty options, I found a game that was somewhat similar to some of the tech mods for minecraft, but with far more depth and coherence.   But this game, unlike minecraft, or most other mining games for that matter, requires you to build infrastructure that mines and processes for you, rather than you mining yourself.   The early mining process requires you to locate a sutible ore vein, plop down a ore extracter on it, stick a storage hopper on it, and dump a bunch of power into it, and leave it for about 10 minuites before coming back, recharging it, and taking the ore to refine.However, every step of that process is automatable, from the very start of the game.   Progression gives you faster, more efficient ways to mine, and automate the mining devices, while encouraging you to dig deeper to get access to more valuable ores, to research and build more advanced and effective machines.Pros-Advancing tech keeps you building and modifying structures-Tower defense aspect adds mid and end game goals-Scanning and visual tools lets you quickly plan out the most efficent way to set up and debug structures-All the information needed to progress can be found in game, no immersion breaking forum trips needed-Large difficulty range-Multiplayer (Still buggy, will likely be improving with time)-EXPLOSIVES that you can make as powerful as you have power for (maybe not so great in multiplayer)Cons-Not much in the way of a wiki to look up information for optimizing setups, particularly base defense-Single threaded- hard to run unless your computer has relatively good single thread performance (I have an AMD 3.7 GHz processor, and I have to run it on a lower graphics setting to avoid framerate drops)-Mob difficulty tends to get grouped- if you want things to fight back, you also have to deal with ore eating mobs that spawn on your conveyers.-Falling too fast kills you, makes it somewhat hard to go down mineshafts, you have to spend a fair amount of time building and navigating stairwells or platforms-Some dead spots while waiting for materials to be mined or refined"
