76561198040590975,Recommended,254200,24488295,"Posted: 23 July, 2016",all,Findail,"FCE is a voxel-based game.  That is where any similarities to that oft-compared ""other highly popular voxel-based game"" ends.  The point of FortressCraft is to build your base/machinery/infrastructure, and let it do the work for you.You start out having crash-landed on a planet with with the most basic of machinery.  Your Central Power Hub to produce power, a research station to perform basic research, a smelter to smelt ore into bars, for use in the crafting station.  Selecting the easier resource difficulty levels will also give you a bonus coal deposit right near your CPH with the machinery needed to automate coal delivery right off the bat.You then start finding resource deposits, placing extractors to mine from them, and collecting ore to smelt to then craft the machinery needed to automate that whole process.  As you discover different types of blocks, you can perform research to be able to craft new machinery to work faster or perform other tasks.  Once your basic research at the research station is all complete, you'll need to build a laboratory to continue higher levels of research.Once you've got your infrastructure rolling along nicely, producing metal bars and power at a good rate, your base threat will increase to the point that the wasps start attacking.  Thus begins the tower defense aspect of the game.  You'll need to build a defense network to deal with the bugs.  And, of course, upgrade that network as your research and production levels increase, to deal with increasingly strong bugs.The best part of this game, though, is the developer.  DjArcas is constantly adding new content into the game, and live streams development quite often.  A lot of game developers claim to be highly involved with their community.  And some even live up to that claim.  But Dj is the only one I know of that interacts with his community live on Twitch while he's writing the code for things that he's talking with the community about.  Many of the machines currently in the game are the result of suggestions made while he was streaming development.If you like voxel-based games, city-building games, or strategy games, or any combination thereof, I highly recommend you check out FortressCraft Evolved."
,Recommended,254200,24528739,"Posted: 25 July, 2016",all,Morally Bankrupt,"It's good.  If you enjoy Factorio, Minecraft tech mods, you'll probably enjoy this.  Don't buy it if you want a quick game, where stuff is just given to you.  There aren't any shortcuts and you'll be building a lot, especially early, to really get things automated.  I got it during the last sale, game + DLC for $17 and it is definitely worth every penny."
,Recommended,254200,26307981,"Posted: 29 October, 2016",all,TheSandsofFlowingTime,"Great game overall. Lots of time to spend playing this and you keep trying to make your base less cluttered, but have to try many different setups before you find a good way to organise everything. While it is annoying that you have to buy DLC for the other half of the game, you kinda get used to not having those items. But then you reach a point where you want to go further, but can't because all of the ores later are too hard for you to get at the time and you don't know what they might be used for, but can't get to."
,Recommended,254200,31250908,Posted: 20 April,all,Greyskye,"**I previously wrote this game a negative review based on a ton of errors I had when I first loaded it off Steam. It turned out that the flashing background, slow building lag, invisible terrain, and archive crashes were all being caused by the graphics drivers provided by Windows 10 during their switchover from OS 8, so if you are having similar problems, do a fresh graphics driver install from NVIDIA or AMD and it will likely clear it up.**Gameplay Pros:- The game provides a ton of options for building the automated mining operation of your dreams, and poses any number of real time logistical puzzles for you to solve. If you enjoy design based problem solving of that sort, this is a great game for you.- Spelunking in the treacherous underworld beneath your base is very enjoyable, with just enough light to make the occasional monster proximity sound very creepy. Expect to do some twitch spins when you hear something sneaking way too close behind you in the ice layer.- The grappling hook is a blast, except when it murders you by failing in the ice layer.- The smart help system is a great innovation that should be copied throughout the genre. It considers what you are looking at on the screen when you hit H and sorts your list accordingly. Simple. Genius.Gameplay Cons:- The core defense system is very, very primitive, to the point where it just seems tacked on. The only base attacker is a wasp swarm. Not weird alien wasps with tentacles or horns in weird places, they're just wasps. Everything else in this setting is alien and unsettling, then you get attacked by something you have killed in your back yard with a can of RAID. (To be fair, the end game wave is more alien looking, but that is hundreds of hours in for most players, after the normal wasps have already ruined the immersion.)- The wasps only vary in size and HP. They don't gain new tactics, they don't start attacking you or the cannons or the cannon supply lines. They just fly in the same straight line to the base each time, and shoot slime at it until it goes offline. For 30 seconds, then it is back and nothing has changed. Until you get to end game, there is very little reason to even bother defending the base, unless you are playing on the highest difficulty, in which case one failure to defend will wipe out weeks worth of work by instantly ending your game. There really is no middle ground there.- The base defense(s) are/is a cannon on a tripod. It changes color as you get higher tiers of it, but it's still the same cannon. The primary challenge of defending your base is keeping the battery charged on said cannon during the zerg wave. That's it. No phalanx anti-air weapons, no rail guns, no tesla coils, no anti-matter fountains. Just the cannon. End game, you can get some missiles, and that's it for your sci-fi arsenal. Cannons and missiles. I do like the defense spider-bot, however. Even though he is automated and requires no strategy or input from the user to function, he is a good example of a cool sci-fi style weapon you might expect in that setting.-Death by pop-up. It was acceptable when I was playing puzzle games on my Macintosh computer as a kid. In 2017, it just seems lazy. You're walking along and you see a big alien in the distance. You go to investigate the big alien and suddenly a Dune sandworm pops out of the ground and you are dead, with a snarky pop-up to announce said death. No fight, no panicked grab for your rifle, no dodging or strafing, no shield damage or heart loss. Pop, death, Death Pop-up. Start over.Or you are ascending your newly dug deep core tunnel on your way back to your base when you pass a blue layer of rock in the middle of your flight. You tap your grappler to make the next ascent, but nothing happens. No ""cold sensation"" or icing warning on the grappler. It just doesn't work anymore. You drop, grappler still does nothing even though you are now in a warm layer. Splat. Death. Death Pop-up. Start over.Or you get past the Dune sandworm and go investigate the giant alien overmind you saw before. At an unmarked distance from the overmind, but well before you actually touch it... you guessed it, Death Pop-up. Start over.It isn't to say there shouldn't be dire risk. There must be dire risk for the game to be fun. In fact, I think the risk to your base from the wave attacks should be higher. But this is a game. In playing a game, the ""playing"" part should be emphasized. There is no game-play element to death by pop-up. Lots of people enjoy the challenge of a good fight, but very few enjoy being randomly brained or splattered with no option to defend oneself.All of that aside, the logistics puzzles and the spelunking alone make for a fun experience. If you can ignore the tacked-on nature of the combat/defense element, I'd still say give it a try when you see it on sale."
