76561198190174953,Not Recommended,254200,21728169,"Posted: 9 March, 2016",all,moi0Alex,"My  Game does not stop crashing, it crashed 3 times in 67 mins ."
76561198019550271,Not Recommended,254200,26278352,"Posted: 28 October, 2016",all,obstructor,"Fast version:  This game is slow, the temperature mechanic is interesting but frustrating, the game is complicated in a non fun way, building things is okay and the monsters are annoying in a non fun way.  Everything is constantly in a state of waiting on everything else, playtime is the devs #1 selling point. Get factorio instead.FortressCraft Evolved is like factorio mixed with minecraft.  With all the cons of both.******************************************************************************************Complexity******************************************************************************************Factorio gets its complexity through simplicity.  FortressCraft gets its complexity through complexity.Factorio has these eight raw resources: wood, coal, iron, copper, stone, oil, water, alien artifacts.  Very different and used for different ends; of these most everything is done with: iron, copper, oil.  Simple, it becomes complex as your create new resources.FortressCraft has 14 (? by the wiki) ores alone, each one can be turned into plates, wires, coils, pipes, and PCBs.  It also has 13 (?) other resources which you find, they can be very hard to find based on your starting seed. (Organic Rock I am looking at you).  FortressCraft also has 11-13 (?) items dropped from mobs that you need to collect.I will start with my frustrations with organic rock.  You need organic rock to make smelters, why? I have no idea.  Organic rock is sometimes found in caves.  Caves are dark and cold.  You only have so much battery to keep yourself warm and the cave lit, so bring 1000 torches made from coal they provide light and warmth.  But don't stand too close or they will begin to overheat your suit, stand precisely something like 1.5 blocks away from it or it is worse than not having one.The first time you look for organic rock it will be easier as you can scan for unknown objects, not all of them will show up but hopefully a couple will.  As a new player instead of collecting all of them you will likely be like, ""wtf is this weird thing, i'll scan it for the research when I get back.""  After this there is no organic rock scan to use later.All this to make a couple smelters.  But smelters also require tin plates and Basic PCB (the copper ones) and all the dependent research.  See the problem.  Fortunately the game starts you off with one smelter you can use, that will deliver you the high throughput of 4 bars per minute at a 4:1 ore to bar ratio.  This leads to maybe being able to make a smelter within the first hour of playing.  Don't worry you will definitely be mining enough ore with the extractors provided. The game will constantly bug you to improve the extractors and also bug you that they are constantly offline as they are backed up. If only I could smelt all this ore.You will be manually running around fetching ore for several hours as conveyors require a copper bar and a tin bar per square. 2 bars each, 2 conveyors per minute, need hundreds of conveyors to connect mines to smelters.Then you need to build the machinery to make plates, wires, coils, PCBs.  Keep in mind storage is very hard to come by as hoppers are very expensive early on, so you can't just build a storage bin for each of these materials immediately.Now you can make the research lab (if you didn't accidently spend all your research points on everything else and screw yourself permanently.)  The lab itself takes a lot of copper, but smelting copper is trivial right?  That isn't the problem with the lab though, the lab can consume 15000 power per second (pps) and the assembler can consume something like 500-1000 pps.  Up until this point power has been trivial, an extractor takes roughly 2 pps, the smelter takes somewhere around 5-10 pps.Do not connect your lab directly to your central power hub, it will take all the power just to charge its own internal buffer.To combat this you need to make more power generators and energy lazers and probably make a new coal mine at this point, so while you are waiting on the metal to set this up, you are waiting on the lab to finish its research, also did I mention that about now you are going to get attacked, better build turrets.  Also did I mention that your lithium mine will probably have a bunch of plants eating all the ore on the conveyor you built, better build some more turrets and batteries and lazers to power it all.  But you need those for the lab too, better get more smelters going, but guess what your suit also needs all that power so you can find more organic rock without dying of hypothermia.  Also you can't leave your base because a bunch of wasps are attacking and they don't seem to stop coming and you need that lithium to build those batteries and the purple plants keep spawning and you need to shoot them too.So you run around killing wasps, trying not to die from hypothermia, out of research points, making sure lithium isn't getting eaten, and collecting metal bars so you can hopefully do something is this silly game.You have now been playing for ten hours.******************************************************************************************How it fails******************************************************************************************It is so hard to explain how needlessy complex and slow this game is.To pull from minecraft and factorio, the furnace is made out of stone blocks.  It makes perfect sense, the limiting factor is how much ore I can find.  Which leads to needing more furnaces, which leads to more ore, etc.  It is an exponential that I want to ride up.To mine something in FortressCraft it needs an extractor, lets assume we have those.  They need power, each one needs at least a basic laser of power.  Lets assume we have those.  They each need to have line of sight to that laser or have batteries to connect them all and the laser needs to be powered likely by another laser.So what should happen is I run back and forth making this mine amazing and making my smelting amazing too.  But you are bottlenecked constantly.  Your new basic smelters will take 8 ore per bar, so we need about 4 extractors.  Which is 4 basic lasers, which is either going to be some crazy triangular setup to keep line of sight or you are going to need 16 ish batteries.  For each of the three basic ores, maybe more lasers for lithium as it is found deeper underground and more everything for copper as you will need a lot.That many lasers just isn't going to happen early on so we will need to upgrade.  Good news there is a better type of laser available early on, the MK1 laser is 10x stronger than the basic laser.  So we can just point one in that direction easy.  Next the conveyor belt can only carry one ore at a time, so perhaps we need to use normal conveyors instead of basic conveyors but replacing the conveyor is being bottlenecked by the very smelting we are trying to upgrade.  So lets just smelt the bars right at the mine its an 8:1 throughput increase.But each smelter takes a full MK1 beam of power, now you are running multiple MK1 lasers to your mine and you have the same problem you had before.  Plus smelters stop working at lower elevations (for some reason?).FortressCraft is like 4+ seperate linear functions instead of one happy exponential.  And once you finally decide to stop increasing one of those functions none of the others can increase either.  For myself it was power for the lab, I just stood there feeding plates, PCB, and research packs into the lab for hours.  It was already running 10 power generators out of energy, even at that my 1 million coal mine was already draining faster than I would like.It is always the same answer: There is a solution to that, that you can't make.  I can't even talk about how research works as I am out of space. Basically you scan unknown blocks, there are only so many unique blocks in this game."
,Not Recommended,254200,24266492,"Posted: 11 July, 2016",all,DONOTSENDCHAT,game is still in beta. a lot of missing standered features you except in game like working menues.i brought this up how this game still feels like in beta in the fourms and got told ya this game still getting new features installed.uh felt cheated buying a product that was advertised as finished.
76561197975421288,Not Recommended,254200,31114660,Posted: 13 April,all,JD,"It starts so well, it is like Factorio or similar factory/base building games, but being in 3d makes it a lot more exciting. The problem is that after a while, you have the basic factory and there is nothing else to build. You do unlock some more objects but they are crafted in a moment and then placed and then you are done. So you are adding occasional new little machines or boxes, but you aren't actually building a base, and you certainly aren't building a 'fortress'. There is really no fortress or base building at all, you just build a basic factory, and then instead of tower defense, you just build 4 lasers and put one in each corner of your base and it kills everything. Later you need to upgrade that by adding a rocket to each corner but you will complete the game like that. There is really no tower defense gameplay in here, no shaping the paths and no multiple tower types with synergy etc. It is just a line of flying monsters that head straight to your core and get killed by lasers when you aren't even there. And even if they don't die, it doesn't matter because there is no penalty for them killing your core. It just regenerates and is back to normal 2 minutes later.The game seems great at first, but it all falls apart after a while and you see how under developed the whole game is. I suggest getting Factorio instead because although that game is 2d and doesn't have the exploring and digging for resources, the actual factory building is more fun, more balanced, and less of a micro management chore. Also the combat is more promising because at least you have to fight back in that game. Also there are a more and better mods, including one that lets you fight back with planes etc. FortressCraft has some mods but not many, and most of them don't do much. You might get a new storage box or something but there isn't anything that adds anything significant to spice up the gameplay.Almost an amazing game but falls short.Factorio is the same by the way, could have been interesting but falls short."
76561197968697930,Not Recommended,254200,9204738,"Posted: 21 February, 2014",all,Frozen Yoghurt,"This game is in early alpha and might be a lot of fun, when it is completed.At the moment however, it lacks the simple design of its predecessors (i.e. Minecraft?) which left me cursing several times.It all starts with a rather buggy menu - there is a small camera driven animation which hovers in front of several signs....which - unlike any current games - do not light up when the mouse hovers over them.Getting into a single player mission is even worse because you have to click the empty space in the middle of the screen (no text or anything like that to actually tell you to do so).When creating a world, the dialogs appear unresponsive. (you click the button - wait for a second or two, click again, ... until you are thrown into the world)In game there are some nice mechanics, namely the survival against the wild system. (your suit keeps you warm on a frozen planet and if its power is fully depleted, you die after a short time).But in my opinion, this is one of the biggest flaws at the moment:There is a brutal world out there, trying to kill you and you have to fight it from the very beginning - without much help or direction from the game.While several games have recently tried this ""do what you like and see what comes of it!""-approach, this game has you fighting for your life from the very first moment and thereby hinders any attempt at  a shallow start (again, think Minecraft: hacking away at those mud-cubes, only to find out they're almost worthless - but you didn't die from that and could switch over to actually mining something useful)However, there are too many unexplained phenomenons to actually rush into this game without any knowledge.After reading a few guides it might start to make sense that you should simply search for coal to power your equipment - but if you've yet to read those guides you might spend the first attempt at survival cursing.Simply because you start with several fancy technologies in your inventory and can't place them or know what to do with them in the first place.Then there is the awkward mining process - it feels counterintuitive having to repeatedly press the mouse button to mine. (why can't I keep it pressed like in Minecraft and it simply keeps mining?)I'd say its got potential once several flaws are fixed.But at the moment there are simply too little hints to actually get started and enjoy the game without reading several guides."
76561198033431815,Not Recommended,254200,16117202,"Posted: 1 June, 2015",all,CrackLoafy,"--Update 8/15/15--Dev warns Steam users not to purchase game.""DjArcas ‏@Fortress_Craft Aug 13Review : ""You should not have released this feature until it was 100% bug-free""YOU shouldn't have bought an Early Access game. ¬.¬""---FortressCraft could have been a really great game, but I cannot recommend it in good faith. I say ""could have been"" because development has all but stopped, even though it's still in Early Access. There are currently game-breaking bugs, such as segment loading/saving errors that result in lost items/constructions, invisible walls, unloaded blocks, etc. Sometimes half the world just doesn't load and everything you've built gets deleted.What is FortressCraft Evolved?There are two modes: Creative and Survival. Creative is the same as any other generic Minecraft clone. Survival is a bit more interesting, and it's where I spent most of my hours in-game. The premise of the Survival mode is a mix between Factorio and Minecraft, where your mission is to basically collect resources and build infrastructure with the end goal of...automating the collection of resources to let you build more stuff. There are ""plans"" to include enemies/combat to give a bit more of a challenge for players who don't just want to mine. Right now exploration isn't that fun. It's a fairly bleak surface world with repetitive caverns below.Why Should I NOT Buy This Game?Game-breaking bugsLack of updates from dev teamPoorly thought out game elements (e.g. The math behind power delivery is completely broken. When you connect batteries, they do not share power instantly, it ""leaks out"" over time. Even with fully upgraded lasers, which transfer power from object to object, it's impossible to fully power the most advanced types of objects currently in game, such as MatterMovers)*Fairly boring/lack of content after first few hours (Granted, that would be fine for any Early Access title, butthis game has been in Early Access for YEARS now and has completely stalled)*Note: Some of these issues have been fixed by a third-party mod, called LazyMod.Yes, a player made fixes to the game that the developer wouldn't/couldn't.The game Developer then asked the mod author on aSteam forumhow he was able to manage these things...that's a bit disheartening.Why Should I Buy This Game?You enjoy automation/upgrading/resource collectionYou don't mind weird glitches, placeholder graphics, or reverting game save filesYou want to support an independent developer who has, in all honesty, probably lost interest in the game"
