76561198277958308,Recommended,254200,24680836,"Posted: 2 August, 2016",all,UbuntuMiner,"A really fun game. Well worth the money, and I am actually considering buying the expansion pack. I got the game in early access, and have really enjoyed playing through the early changes in the game."
76561198048623723,Recommended,254200,26433472,"Posted: 5 November, 2016",all,Skynred,"This game is to Factorio what Minecraft is to Terraria. (If you didn't get that: Fortresscraft Evolved is a 3D Factorio.)It is complex and requires some patience/time to get the hang of things but, once you do, it's a blast. You go to sleep thinking about how you're gonna automate the extraction of ores, how to optimize power distribution, etc., and wake up eager to put your ideas in practice. If you are not afraid of some hard work and like figuring out how to make things work efficiently, you're probably gonna love this game.It also must be mentioned that this game is being done (you could say it's still in Early Access, there's a lot of content yet to come) by a single guy, which is baffling.----------I'm going to adress some of the points raised by most of the negative reviews to try and set your mind at ease in case you are considering buying Fortresscraft Evolved--and because I believe this game deserves much more praise than it seems to be getting:1 - It has some rough edges indeed (a few Help texts missing, some not quite clear, conveyor belts blinking every now and then, the Spiderbot getting stuck, ...) but they are all minor issues. All the machines and everything else that matters works perfectly. Since the game is being developed by one person, I think that's forgivable and his priorities make sense.2 - The UI is not beautiful, but you get used to it really fast and it fulfills its purpose just fine.3 - The tutorial kinda sucks indeed (you gotta take a look around your base to spot some signs telling you what to interact with and how) but it gives you the basics and its extremely short (I hate long ones.) A small message will pop up on the top right corner of your screen after the mini-tutorial is done to suggest you what to do next so you don't get lost. If you keep an eye on the help-box on the lower left corner of the screen when you point at something, and check the Help Book when needed, you can figure pretty much everything out. (Land your pointer on any item in your inventory then press H and said item will show up on the top of the Help list... I think it's neat how that works.)4 - Some claim the Dev is an A-Hole. Well, I never talked to him directly nor anything but I've seem him answering appropriately and politely to every single Steam-forum topic/question I looked up. The guy seems to work a lot and hard, apparently answers every single question about his game personally and who knows what else, and we, players, can also be annoying with our requests/demands/suggestions quite often so... I think the guy is doing the best he can, I didn't actually see anything that made him look like a jerk.5 - I read about performance issues. I, myself, have an average computer and run Fortresscraft with fixed 60fps and never had any issues other than the eventual crash (rare, about 6 in 70 hours playing so far.)6 - ""The DLC policy."" Okay, this does suck at first glance. The game is not really finished and there's already a DLC. When you are playing, your research one tech tree or go down to a certain layer of the underground and realize you can't mine these ores because you don't have the DLC, or can't build some of the stuff you just researched for the same reason. It♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥me off too--specially because nothing warns you you need the DLC to do this or that, it's just there like everything else and then... you can't do it (and that's the worst flaw in the game for me.) But then I went to take a look at the Devs writings and some other stuff and... well, the game sells well during sales, but not so much in between them. The guy needs money, like everyone else. But the thing is: he deserves it.I was playing and run into the problems I just mentioned. I quit it to check on the DLC and wonder whether I should get it or not (not on sale, and it costs 30 bucks here in my country while it must be 10 or so for Americans... and our wages are lower as well so I'm paying, essentially, about 6 times more for it.) Well, long story short, after I read everything I did (the Dev's Patreon page, the spread sheet with his schedule for future updates, ...) I just came back and got the DLC, for the reason I said above--I believe the guy deserves it. Fortresscraft is a great game but, sadly, its sales rate doesn't do it justice. So I'm helping him out by buying a buckload of content with the Frozen Factory expansion (only one other game ever inspired me to help out, and that was Tales of Maj'Eyal.)7 - Most of the other complaints seem to be mistakes. People who couldn't find a certain item, or figure out how to decently farm a drop, or where to find something else. I had no problem of the sort--it's all there. In the worst case scenario, you can Google it and you'll find the solution.----------So, summing up: Fortresscraft Evolved is great fun and pretty solid for a one-dev game. If you get it (and I recommend you do) I suggest you get the DLC as well. If you don't, by the time you need it you'll realize it's worth its price and probably end up buying it anyway, like I did.And don't be intimidated by the game's screenshots. Fortresscraft Evolved is intricate, but it's not that garish fanfare they make it seem to be--unless you want it, of course, but it's totally NOT necessary.----------One last detail: you can become a ""Patreon"" by donating 10 bucks or so monthly to the Dev (so with the steady income he can hire a 2D and 3D artists to help him out.) Patreons get some aesthetical bonus items and beta-access to new stuff.----------EDIT: Ok, now that I sank some 200 more hours into the game, I gotta say you spend a lot of time just waiting for resources to pile up--and by ""a lot"" I mean about 2/3 of the time.The base game ""ends"" when you charge the OET (Orbital Energy Transmitter or, as I like to call it, the Over-Exaggerated Timewaster.) Anyone who played 150 hours or more spent about 100 of them just piling up resources to have enough power to charge this thing and defenses to survive the non-stop, overpowered waves of monsters that come when you actually start charging it. If you manage to do everything right (enough power, enough defenses) it's gonna take you about 10 hours to charge the OET once. You gotta do it 4 times. You just sit there, waiting while it charges, because there's nothing left to do until it does.After that's done, you get into the DLC (if you have it, of course, which I do.) At first it's fine, then it starts to get a bit grindy once again, until you are finally able to build a machine called ""The Magmaborer"" which is to the game's expansion what the OET is to the base game. But, doing some quickly calculations, it turns out it's about 25 times worse than the OET. I closed the game--and never went back to it--as soon as I realized that (the OET itself has already been the biggest time-waster and the most artificial game-time increaser I've ever seen in my life.)That stuff needs to be balanced.Nonetheless, when you're actually PLAYING the game, it's great--so my positive recommendation stands. Even with the OET crap and the Magmaborer even-crappier crap, I'm still glad I bought this game (and the DLC as well.)"
