,Recommended,254200,27357843,"Posted: 24 November, 2016",all,FireDragon,"This game is absolutely fantastic.One major plus to the game is that the main developer (DJArcas) streams a lot of his creation process, between bug fixes and new features, and is relatively easy to get in contact with in a variety of ways- causing a unique sense of being part of the game's creation.The game itself is amazing. Starting with the graphics, all of them are fabulous. They might as well be considered the best- loading very quickly, with little to no lag, unlike most games that try to have good graphics (even with a not-so-good laptop or PC!).On to the gameplay, there is a ton of content, tons of machines to build and resources to gather, while still not flooding the player with too many options. There is a story, somewhat, as well. You crash on a planet and try to get off (this is definitely not the best description of the story), which adds a point to the game, rather than pointless building.This may not be the most coherent review ever, but these are the main reasons (among many other) why I have nominated this game for one of the Steam Awards."
76561198007897761,Recommended,254200,30483552,Posted: 12 March,all,etheric42,"I just can't go back to laying down one conveyer belt per click after playing Factorio.*edit*Turns out I was wrong!  And so were the YouTube videos I watched!  Steam Reviews works again!Still have more time before the next Factorio patch, so will try again this week.  Would have been nice if the interface or in-game help had explained this after I had laid down the ore miner or looked up conveyer belts in the in-game help, but I understand many games are too busy being awesome to explain themselves.*edit edit*Well, previously this was a negative review.  This isn't wholely a positive review either, wish there was some more shades in the middle for Steam.  As I mentioned previously there are some teaching issues.  Mass-building/build-to-me really should be in more help files or hand-hold explained (not the rest, but something as core as that should be clearly laid out from the start, especially on any kind of not-hard-mode).  At the very least it should show up in the help files of commonly mass-built things like conveyer belts.  Additionally the quest/tutorial system that is trying to tell me generally what to try building next started useful but then got very seperated from my current progress, recommending things that I had already done/experimented with a long time ago at sometimes and then recommending things that are way past my tech level (or usefulness) at others.Also, you don't normally expect a Nvidia 1080 with a i5-6500 CPU to hit framerate issues in games, but the center of my base where most of my conveyer belts meet causes noticible chug.  Some gameplay mechanics to encourage spreading out or optimizations would be useful.I also prefer the inserter model from Factorio instead of the way hoppers and belts interact here (that may be due to me paying Factorio first, but I am fine with the different ways they do power).But... building conveyer belts in 3d... digging and building elevator shafts... carting energy to deep mines and barely making it back to the surface before hypothermia sets in....  Very enjoyable in a similar but different way than Factorio.  (although similar to factorio, killing bugs is a bit meh, and the starting wasps have a longer range than the starting turrets, which is frustrating)*edit edit edit*Framerate issues fixed.  When the game starts up, the launcher was pre-set to ""fantastic"".  Downgrade that to ""good"" and the graphics quality does not noticibly go down, but the framerate improves around your core considerably.  Turns out the developers consider ""good"" the effective top-tier for their game.  That's fine, but was not expected and I didn't feel it was communicated that well compared to expectations for that kind of launcher."
